 the Nation: The Production of National Citizens in Greek Primary Education -- tPart III. Special Contributions -- tChapter 10. Anthropology and/in Intercultural Education in Italy: The Winding Roads to Diversity and Identity -- tChapter 11. Civil Enculturation in the Netherlands, Britain, Germany, and France: A Look Back and Ahead -- tAfterword. Toward an Anthropology of Education in Europe: Insights, Challenges, and Potentials -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPresenting European Anthropology of Education through eleven studies of European schools, this volume explores the constructing and handling of difference and sameness in the central institutions of schools. Based on ethnographic studies of schools in Greece, England, Norway, Italy, Switzerland, the Czech Republic, Spain, Austria, Russia, Germany, the Netherlands and Denmark, it illustrates how anthropological studies of schools provide a window to larger society. It thus offers insights into cultural lessons taught to children through policies, institutional structures and everyday interactions, as well as into schools’ entanglement in state projects, cultural processes, societal histories and conflicts, and hence into contemporary Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAhajjaj, Jamal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBittnerová, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoubek, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilliam, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilliam, Laura, eedito